{
  "doc_id": "9565",
  "text": "It is also well-known that besides the GHG emissions, the construction and operation of buildings inflict other environmental effects. For example, [CITATION_1] included four other environmental aspects besides GHGs in their study, which focused on the life cycle environmental impacts of office buildings. The other aspects were acidification, summer smog, eutrophication and heavy metals [CITATION_2] . Blengini et al. (2010) studied cumulative energy demand, non-renewable energy demand and potentials for global warming, ozone depletion, acidification, eutrophication and photochemical ozone creation in their LCA of an Italian low-energy residential building [CITATION_3] . [CITATION_4] studied the potential of acidification of land and water, eutrophication, global warming, depletion of the stratospheric and tropospheric ozone layers plus uses of renewable and non-renewable energy resources in their LCA of technical building equipment on residential buildings [CITATION_5] . [CITATION_6] included global warming potential, acidification, eutrophication and photochemical ozone formation in his comparison of two similar houses built with either new or recycled building materials [CITATION_7] .",
